oad form (POST to / with parameter `pickle_file`)\\n4. The server deserializes the pickle, executes the payload, and deletes decoy.txt\\n5. Subsequent page loads will display the real flag from flag.txt instead of the decoy\\n\\n## Validation / Evidence\\n- Validation token / flag: Not observed (reconnaissance phase only)\\n- Tool evidence: Direct HTTP GET request and response analysis\\n- Request evidence:\\n  ```\\n  GET / HTTP/1.1\\n  Host: 127.0.0.1:32942\\n  ```\\n- Response evidence:\\n  ```html\\n  <h5>The current flag is: this is just the decoy </h5>\\n  \\n  <pre>if os.path.exists(\'decoy.txt\'):\\n      flag = open(\'decoy.txt\').read()\\n  else:\\n      flag = open(\'flag.txt\').read()</pre>\\n  \\n  <form action=\\"/\\" method=\\"post\\" enctype=\\"multipart/form-data\\">\\n  <input type=\\"file\\" id=\\"pickle_file\\" name=\\"pickle_file\\">\\n  <button type=\\"submit\\">Upload pickle</button>\\n  </form>\\n  ```\\n- Notes on reliability / limitations: \\n  - The application exposes full server-side logic revealing the exploitation path\\n  - File upload accepts pickle files without validation or sanitization\\n  - Exploitation requires successful deserialization and execution of the payload\\n\\n## Remediation\\n- Root cause: The application uses `pickle.load()` on user-supplied file content without validation. The vulnerable logic exposes the exploitation path by checking for decoy.txt existence to determine flag display.\\n- Recommended fix:\\n  1. Replace pickle deserialization with JSON or another safe serialization format\\n  2. If pickle is required, implement a cryptographic signature (HMAC) to verify file integrity\\n  3. Use `pickle.Unpickler` with restricted `find_class` to whitelist allowed classes\\n  4. Do not execute OS operations based on deserialized untrusted data\\n- Defense-in-depth: Run deserialization in an isolated/sandboxed environment with minimal privileges\\n\\n## How to Verify the Fix\\n1. Upload the malicious pickle payload 